{
  "_metadata": {
    "model": "claude-fable-5",
    "cost_usd": 0.199856,
    "duration_s": 50.002
  },
  "tool_calls": [
    {
      "name": "Bash",
      "args": {
        "command": "ls stm32-project.jsonc 2>/dev/null && cat stm32-project.jsonc 2>/dev/null; pwd",
        "description": "Check for project descriptor in cwd"
      }
    },
    {
      "name": "Bash",
      "args": {
        "command": "stm32 prog list-probes",
        "description": "List attached ST-LINK probes"
      }
    },
    {
      "name": "Bash",
      "args": {
        "command": "STM32_PROGRAMMER_DEFAULT_SN=066DFF485754727567021514 stm32 debug read-peripheral RCC",
        "description": "SVD-decoded dump of live RCC registers on L476RG"
      }
    },
    {
      "name": "Bash",
      "args": {
        "command": "python3 -c \"\nimport json\nd=json.load(open('/home/anup/.claude/projects/-home-anup-claude-projects-stm32-substrate-tests-fixtures-projects-F-PROJ-NUCLEO-L476RG/1e3c861b-4440-4b0c-939a-28821cbc92f1/tool-results/bcjd1emo3.txt'))\nfor reg in ('CFGR','PLLCFGR'):\n    r=d['registers'][reg]\n    print(reg, hex(r['raw_value']))\n    for f,v in r['fields'].items(): print(' ', f, v['raw_value'])\n\"",
        "description": "Extract CFGR and PLLCFGR fields from RCC dump"
      }
    }
  ],
  "final_text": "Two probes on the bench \u2014 the descriptor is the L476RG BLINKY project, so I'll pin the ST-LINK V2 probe and read the live RCC state (attach without reset, halt in place):\nYes \u2014 the clock tree is fully initialized and you're at **80 MHz SYSCLK**, the expected max-speed config for the L476 examples. Decoding the live RCC state (read without reset, so this is the running firmware's configuration):\n\n**Clock path: MSI 4 MHz \u2192 PLL \u00d740/2 \u2192 80 MHz**\n\n| Stage | Field | Value | Meaning |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Source osc | `MSIRANGE=6`, `MSIRGSEL=1`, `MSIRDY=1` | MSI @ **4 MHz**, ready | PLL input |\n| PLL source | `PLLSRC=1` | MSI feeds the PLL | |\n| PLL math | `PLLM=0` (/1), `PLLN=40`, `PLLR=0` (/2) | 4 \u00d7 40 / 2 = **80 MHz** | VCO at 160 MHz \u2014 in range |\n| PLL status | `PLLON=1`, `PLLRDY=1`, `PLLREN=1` | Locked, R output enabled | \u2705 |\n| SYSCLK mux | `SW=3`, `SWS=3` | PLL **requested and confirmed** as SYSCLK | \u2705 no mux mismatch |\n| Bus dividers | `HPRE=0`, `PPRE1=0`, `PPRE2=0` | HCLK = APB1 = APB2 = **80 MHz** | All /1 |\n\nHealth checks:\n\n- **SW == SWS** \u2014 the switch actually completed; firmware isn't stuck waiting on the mux.\n- **PLLRDY=1 with the source (MSI) ready** \u2014 clean lock, no fallback to MSI happened.\n- HSI16 and HSE are both off (`HSION=0`, `HSEON=0`) \u2014 intentional; the Nucleo's stock config runs MSI\u2192PLL. `CSSON=0`, so no clock-security event is in play.\n- `MSIPLLEN=0` \u2014 MSI isn't auto-trimmed off LSE; fine for this firmware, just means MSI's \u00b1~1% tolerance carries through to SYSCLK (only matters if you later derive USB or tight baud rates from it).\n\nOne caveat I can't verify from RCC alone: at 80 MHz the flash must be at \u22654 wait states (`FLASH->ACR.LATENCY=4`). If you want, I can read the FLASH peripheral to confirm that too \u2014 say the word."
}